  1. Data preliminaries: Load the data from the “spBayes” package. Create the response variable for biomass in kilograms per hour (KGH), which measures the rate at which woody biomass is consumed or produced. The response is transformed to the logarithmic scale.
data(BEF.dat)
befDat <- BEF.dat[BEF.dat$ALLBIO02_KGH > 0, ]
bio <- befDat$ALLBIO02_KGH * 0.001
logBio <- log(bio)
  1. Extract the coordinates
befCoords <- as.matrix(befDat[, c("XUTM", "YUTM")])
  1. Create a surface plot using the Multilevel B-spline Approximation (MBA).
xRes <- 100
yRes <- 100
surf <- mba.surf(cbind(befCoords, bio), no.X = xRes, no.Y = yRes, h = 5, m = 2, extend = FALSE)$xyz.est
image.plot(surf, xaxs = "r", yaxs = "r", xlab = "Easting (m)", ylab = "Northing (m)",
    main = "Biomass in metric tonnes")
points(befCoords)

  1. Start with a simple Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) regression.
model <- logBio ~ ELEV + SLOPE + SUM_02_TC1 + SUM_02_TC2 + SUM_02_TC3
modelFit <- lm(model, data = befDat)
modelFitSummary <- summary(modelFit)
print(modelFitSummary)  ##Print summary of classical OLS model fit

bioResid = resid(modelFit)  ##Store residuals from the OLS model fit for later use
  1. Prepare for the Bayesian modeling. Extract the number of regression coefficients and create a flat non-informative prior for the regression coefficients.
p <- length(coefficients(modelFit))  ## This is the number of columns in the design matrix
## Set the prior mean and precision for the regression
betaPriorMean <- as.matrix(rep(0, times = p))
betaPriorPrecision <- matrix(0, nrow = p, ncol = p)
  1. Prepare the fixed inputs for “bayesGeostatExact” function.
phi <- 0.014  ## Set the spatial range (from the variogram)
alpha <- 0.016/0.08  ## Set the nugget/partial-sill ratio
sigmaSqPriorShape <- 2  ## Set IG shape for sigma.sq (partial sill)
sigmaSqPriorRate <- 0.08  ## Set IG scale for sigma.sq (partial sill)
  1. Run bayesGeostatExact to deliver exact posterior samples
spExact <- bayesGeostatExact(model, data = befDat, coords = befCoords, n.samples = 1000,
    beta.prior.mean = betaPriorMean, beta.prior.precision = betaPriorPrecision, cov.model = "exponential",
    phi = phi, alpha = alpha, sigma.sq.prior.shape = sigmaSqPriorShape, sigma.sq.prior.rate = sigmaSqPriorRate,
    sp.effects = TRUE)

  1. Run spLM to deliver MCMC samples from marginal posterior distributions
nSamples <- 1000
befSp <- spLM(model, data = befDat, coords = befCoords, starting = list(phi = 3/200,
    sigma.sq = 0.08, tau.sq = 0.02), tuning = list(phi = 0.1, sigma.sq = 0.05, tau.sq = 0.05),
    priors = list(phi.Unif = c(3/1500, 3/50), sigma.sq.IG = c(2, 0.08), tau.sq.IG = c(2,
        0.02)), cov.model = "exponential", n.samples = nSamples)

  1. Produce the posterior summaries from “spLM”
print(round(summary(befSp$p.theta.samples)$quantiles, 3))

  1. Recover spatial residuals using “spRecover”
burnIn <- floor(0.75 * nSamples)
befSp <- spRecover(befSp, start = burnIn, thin = 2)
-------------------------------------------------
        Recovering beta and w
-------------------------------------------------
Sampled: 99 of 126, 78.57%
  1. The posterior samples of the regression coefficients and the spatial effects can then be obtained.
betaSamples = befSp$p.beta.recover.samples
wSamples = befSp$p.w.recover.samples
  1. Obtain trace plots for regression coefficients
par(mfrow = c(3, 2))
plot(betaSamples, auto.layout = TRUE, density = FALSE)

  1. Obtain posterior means and sd’s of spatial residuals for each location
wHatMu <- apply(wSamples, 1, mean)
wHatSd <- apply(wSamples, 1, sd)
  1. Plot the OLS residual surface and a map of the posterior mean of spatial effects
par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
surfResid <- mba.surf(cbind(befCoords, bioResid), no.X = xRes, no.Y = yRes, extend = FALSE)$xyz.est
zLim <- range(surfResid[["z"]], na.rm = TRUE)
image.plot(surfResid, xaxs = "r", yaxs = "r", zlim = zLim, main = "OLS residuals")
surfSpatMean <- mba.surf(cbind(befCoords, wHatMu), no.X = xRes, no.Y = yRes, extend = FALSE)$xyz.est
zLim <- range(surfSpatMean[["z"]], na.rm = TRUE)
image.plot(surfSpatMean, xaxs = "r", yaxs = "r", zlim = zLim, main = "Posterior mean spatial effects")

  1. Carry out spatial interpolation supervised by the points with observations
surfOut <- mba.surf(cbind(befCoords, logBio), no.X = xRes, no.Y = yRes, extend = TRUE)$xyz.est
zLim <- range(surfOut[["z"]], na.rm = TRUE)
  1. Map the interpolated values from MBA output
image.plot(surfOut, axes = TRUE, zlim = zLim, col = tim.colors(25), xaxs = "r", yaxs = "r",
    main = "Log metric tons of biomass")

  1. OPTIONAL: How to create a data frame with all grid point combinations

  1. Here is how we can clip images to fit within a polygon from a shapefile
surfOutRaster <- raster(surfOut$z, xmn = min(surfOut$x), xmx = max(surfOut$x), ymn = min(surfOut$y),
    ymx = max(surfOut$y))
surfOutClipped <- mask(surfOutRaster, befShp)
plot(surfOutClipped, col = tim.colors(25), xaxs = "r", yaxs = "r", main = "Log metric tons of 
biomass: Within polygon")
